text: Flatbush Ave., east side, between Fenimore and Hawthorne Streets. A view of Flatbush Ave., in the background. In the foreground, is a statue once on the estate of Dr. H. L. Bartlett{ whose estate was bound on the north by Fenimore Street, on the south by Hawthorne Street, on the west by Flatbush Ave., and on the east by Bedford Ave). 1900. Eugene L. Armbruster collection.

Toll houses: Views of Brooklyn toll houses. The one shown in views 1,2 stood on Flatbush Avenue between Fenimore and Winthrop Streets.

View 3 shows one that stood on the Jamaica Plank Road.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection  Views 1,2: 1922
View 3: about 1900

title: Brooklyn: Flatbush Avenue - Chester Court

text:
(1)
610 Flatbush Ave., west side, just north of Chester Court; owned by Reuben Freeman in 1911. It was originally the Jeremiah Vanderbilt House which now (1936) is no longer standing.
1910.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(2)
The same, another view. In 1920 it was an automobile supply station until torn down, about 1923. The old Vanderbilt House burnt during the Revolutionary War stood just north of this house.
1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

text:
Flatbush Ave., west side, north from just south of Rutland Road, seen in the right foreground. In the center at left, is Chester Court. The 4-story building occupies the sites of the Birdsall and Vanderbilt homes.

May 1929.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
